# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: directx-graphics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D contains many commands for 3D computer graphics rendering; however, since version 8, Direct3D has superseded the DirectDraw framework and also taken responsibility for the rendering of 2D graphics.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Microsoft strives to continually update Direct3D to support the latest technology available on 3D graphics cards.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D offers full vertex software emulation but no pixel software emulation for features not available in hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The API does include a *Reference Rasterizer* (or REF device), which emulates a generic graphics card in software, although it is too slow for most real-time 3D applications and is typically only used for debugging.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] A new real-time software rasterizer, *WARP*, designed to emulate the complete feature set of Direct3D 10.1, is included with Windows 7 and Windows Vista Service Pack 2 with the Platform Update; its performance is said to be on par with lower-end 3D cards on multi-core CPUs.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] As part of DirectX, Direct3D is available for Windows 95 and above, and is the base for the vector graphics API on the different versions of Xbox console systems.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Wine compatibility layer, a free software reimplementation of several Windows APIs, includes an implementation of Direct3D.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D's main competitor is Khronos' OpenGL and its follow-on Vulkan.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Fahrenheit was an attempt by Microsoft and SGI to unify OpenGL and Direct3D in the 1990s, but was eventually cancelled.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In 1992, Servan Keondjian, Doug Rabson and Kate Seekings started a company named RenderMorphics, which developed a 3D graphics API named Reality Lab, which was used in medical imaging and CAD software.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Microsoft bought RenderMorphics in February 1995, bringing its staff on board to implement a 3D graphics engine for Windows 95.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D initially implemented an "immediate mode" 3D API and layered upon it a "retained mode" 3D API.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Both types of API were already offered with the second release of Reality Lab before Direct3D was released.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Like other DirectX APIs, such as DirectDraw, both were based on COM.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The retained mode API was a scene graph API that attained little adoption.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Game developers clamored for more direct control of the hardware's activities than the Direct3D retained mode could provide.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Only two games that sold a significant volume, *Lego Island* and *Lego Rock Raiders*, were based on the Direct3D retained mode, so Microsoft did not update the retained mode API after DirectX 3.0.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] For DirectX 2.0 and 3.0, the Direct3D immediate mode used an "execute buffer" programming model that Microsoft hoped hardware vendors would support directly.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Execute buffers were intended to be allocated in hardware memory and parsed by the hardware to perform the 3D rendering.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] They were considered extremely awkward to program at the time, however, hindering adoption of the new API and prompting calls for Microsoft to adopt OpenGL as the official 3D rendering API for games as well as workstation applications.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Rather than adopt OpenGL as a gaming API, Microsoft chose to continue improving Direct3D, not only to be competitive with OpenGL, but to compete more effectively with other proprietary APIs such as 3dfx's Glide.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] From the beginning, the immediate mode also supported Talisman's tiled rendering with the BeginScene/EndScene methods of the IDirect3DDevice interface.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] No substantive changes were planned to Direct3D for **DirectX 4.0**, which was scheduled to ship in late 1996 and then cancelled.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In December 1996, a team in Redmond took over development of the Direct3D Immediate Mode, while the London-based RenderMorphics team continued work on the Retained Mode.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Redmond team added the DrawPrimitive API that eliminated the need for applications to construct execute buffers, making Direct3D more closely resemble other immediate mode rendering APIs such as Glide and OpenGL.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The first beta of DrawPrimitive shipped in February 1997, and the final version shipped with **DirectX 5.0** in August 1997.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Besides introducing an easier-to-use immediate mode API, DirectX 5.0 added the SetRenderTarget method that enabled Direct3D devices to write their graphical output to a variety of DirectDraw surfaces.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] A minor update to **DirectX 6.0** came in the February, 1999 DirectX 6.1 update.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Besides adding DirectMusic support for the first time, this release improved support for Intel Pentium III 3D extensions.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] A confidential memo sent in 1997 shows Microsoft planning to announce full support for Talisman in DirectX 6.0, but the API ended up being cancelled (See the Microsoft Talisman page for details).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D was not considered to be user friendly, but as of DirectX version 8.1, many usability problems were resolved.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 8 contained many powerful 3D graphics features, such as vertex shaders, pixel shaders, fog, bump mapping and texture mapping.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Windows Vista includes a major update to the Direct3D API.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Originally called WGF 2.0 (Windows Graphics Foundation 2.0), then DirectX 10 and DirectX Next, **Direct3D 10** features an updated shader model 4.0 and optional interruptibility for shader programs.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In this model shaders still consist of fixed stages as in previous versions, but all stages support a nearly unified interface, as well as a unified access paradigm for resources such as textures and shader constants.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The language itself has been extended to be more expressive, including integer operations, a greatly increased instruction count, and more C-like language constructs.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Windows XP and earlier are not supported by DirectX 10.0 and above.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Furthermore, Direct3D 10 dropped support for the retained mode API which had been a part of Direct3D since the beginning, making Windows Vista incompatible with 3D games that had used the retained mode API as their rendering engine.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Unlike prior versions of the API, Direct3D 10 no longer uses "capability bits" (or "caps") to indicate which features are supported on a given graphics device.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Instead, it defines a minimum standard of hardware capabilities which must be supported for a display system to be "Direct3D 10 compatible".
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This is a significant departure, with the goal of streamlining application code by removing capability-checking code and special cases based on the presence or absence of specific capabilities.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Because Direct3D 10 hardware was comparatively rare after the initial release of Windows Vista and because of the massive install base of non-Direct3D 10 compatible graphics cards, the first Direct3D 10-compatible games still provide Direct3D 9 render paths.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Examples of such titles are games originally written for Direct3D 9 and ported to Direct3D 10 after their release, such as *Company of Heroes*, or games originally developed for Direct3D 9 with a Direct3D 10 path retrofitted later during their development, such as *Hellgate: London* or *Crysis*.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The DirectX 10 SDK became available in February 2007.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 10.1 sets a few more image quality standards for graphics vendors, and gives developers more control over image quality.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Features include finer control over anti-aliasing (both multisampling and supersampling with per sample shading and application control over sample position) and more flexibilities to some of the existing features (cubemap arrays and independent blending modes).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Unlike Direct3D 10 which strictly required Direct3D 10-class hardware and driver interfaces, Direct3D 10.1 runtime can run on Direct3D 10.0 hardware using a concept of "feature levels", but new features are supported exclusively by new hardware which expose feature level 10_1.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The only available Direct3D 10.1 hardware as of June 2008 were the Radeon HD 3000 series and Radeon HD 4000 series from ATI; in 2009, they were joined by Chrome 430/440GT GPUs from S3 Graphics and select lower-end models in GeForce 200 series from Nvidia.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In 2011, Intel chipsets started supporting Direct3D 10.1 with the introduction of Intel HD Graphics 2000 (GMA HD).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Direct3D 11 runtime is able to run on Direct3D 9 and 10.x-class hardware and drivers using the concept of "feature levels", expanding on the functionality first introduced in Direct3D 10.1 runtime.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] There are three "10 Level 9" profiles which encapsulate various capabilities of popular DirectX 9.0a cards, and Direct3D 10, 10.1, and 11 each have a separate feature level; each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Tessellation was earlier considered for Direct3D 10, but was later abandoned.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] GPUs such as Radeon R600 feature a tessellation engine that can be used with Direct3D 9/10/10.1 and OpenGL, but it's not compatible with Direct3D 11 (according to Microsoft).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Older graphics hardware such as Radeon 8xxx, GeForce 3/4 had support for another form of tesselation (RT patches, N patches) but those technologies never saw substantial use.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] As such, their support was dropped from newer hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Microsoft has also hinted at other features such as order independent transparency, which was never exposed by the Direct3D API but supported almost transparently by early Direct3D hardware such as Videologic's PowerVR line of chips.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Other notable features are the addition of two new texture compression algorithms for more efficient packing of high quality and HDR/alpha textures and an increased texture cache.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] First seen in the Release Candidate version, Windows 7 integrates the first released Direct3D 11 support.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Platform Update for Windows Vista includes full-featured Direct3D 11 runtime and DXGI 1.1 update, as well as other related components from Windows 7 like WARP, Direct2D, DirectWrite, and WIC.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] WARP has been updated to support feature level 11_1.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Platform Update for Windows 7 includes a limited set of features from Direct3D 11.1, though components that depend on WDDM 1.2 – such as feature level 11_1 and its related APIs, or quad buffering for stereoscopic rendering – are not present.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 11.X is a superset of DirectX 11.2 running on the Xbox One.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] It includes some features, such as draw bundles, that were later announced as part of DirectX 12.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Pipeline state objects (PSOs) have evolved from Direct3D 11, and the new concise pipeline states mean that the process has been simplified.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] DirectX 11 offered flexibility in how its states could be altered, to the detriment of performance.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Simplifying the process and unifying the pipelines (e.g. pixel shader states) lead to a more streamlined process, significantly reducing the overheads and allowing the graphics card to draw more calls for each frame.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Root signatures introduce configurations to link command lists to resources required by shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] They define the layout of resources that shaders will use and specify what resources will be bound to the pipeline.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] A graphics command list has both a graphics and compute root signature, while a compute command list will have only a compute root signature.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] These root signatures are completely independent of each other.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] While the root signature lays out the types of data for shaders to use, it does not define or map the actual memory or data.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Root parameters are one type of entry in a root signature.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The actual values of the root parameters that are modified at runtime are called root arguments.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Within Direct3D 11, the commands are sent from the CPU to the GPU one by one, and the GPU works through these commands sequentially.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This means that commands are bottlenecked by the speed at which the CPU can send these commands in a linear fashion.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Within DirectX 12 these commands are sent as command lists, containing all the required information within a single package.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The GPU is then capable of computing and executing this command in one single process, without having to wait on any additional information from the CPU.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Where previously commands were just taken, used, and then forgotten by the GPU, bundles can be reused.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This decreases the workload of the GPU and means repeated assets can be used much faster.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] While resource binding is fairly convenient in Direct3D 11 for developers at the moment, its inefficiency means several modern hardware capabilities are being drastically underused.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] When a game engine needed resources in DX11, it had to draw the data from scratch every time, meaning repeat processes and unnecessary uses.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In Direct3D 12, descriptor heaps and tables mean the most often used resources can be allocated by developers in tables, which the GPU can quickly and easily access.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This can contribute to better performance than Direct3D 11 on equivalent hardware, but it also entails more work for the developer.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Dynamic Heaps are also a feature of Direct3D 12.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 12 features explicit multi-adapter support, allowing the explicit control of multiple GPUs (mGPU) configuration systems.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Such configurations can be built with graphics adapter of the same hardware vendor as well of different hardware vendor together.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] An experimental support of D3D 12 for Windows 7 SP1 has been released by Microsoft in 2019 via a dedicated NuGet package.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D is a Microsoft DirectX API subsystem component.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The aim of Direct3D is to abstract the communication between a graphics application and the graphics hardware drivers.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] It is presented like a thin abstract layer at a level comparable to GDI (see attached diagram).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D contains numerous features that GDI lacks.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D is an *Immediate mode* graphics API.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] It provides a low-level interface to every video card 3D function (*transformations, clipping, lighting*, *materials*, *textures*, *depth buffering* and so on).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] It once had a higher level *Retained mode* component, now officially discontinued.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D immediate mode presents three main abstractions: *devices*, *resources* and *Swap Chains* (see attached diagram).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] *Devices* are responsible for rendering the 3D scene.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] They provide an interface with different rendering capabilities.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] For example, the mono device provides white and black rendering, while the RGB device renders in color.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Every device contains at least one *swap chain*.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] A *swap chain* is made up of one or more back buffer surfaces.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Moreover, devices contain a collection of *resources*; specific data used during rendering.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Microsoft Direct3D 11 API defines a process to convert a group of vertices, textures, buffers, and state into an image on the screen.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This process is described as a rendering pipeline with several distinct stages.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Vertex Shader**: Performs operations on a single vertex at a time, such as transformations, skinning, or lighting.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Hull-Shader**: Performs operations on sets of patch control points, and generates additional data known as patch constants.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Tessellator**: Subdivides geometry to create higher-order representations of the hull.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Domain-Shader**: Performs operations on vertices output by the tessellation stage, in much the same way as a vertex shader.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Geometry Shader**: Processes entire primitives such as triangles, points, or lines.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Given a primitive, this stage discards it, or generates one or more new primitives.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Stream-Output**: Can write out the previous stage's results to memory.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This is useful to recirculate data back into the pipeline.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Rasterizer**: Converts primitives into pixels, feeding these pixels into the pixel shader.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The Rasterizer may also perform other tasks such as clipping what is not visible, or interpolating vertex data into per-pixel data.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Pixel Shader**: Determines the final pixel color to be written to the render target and can also calculate a depth value to be written to the depth buffer.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] **Output-Merger**: Merges various types of output data (pixel shader values, alpha blending, depth/stencil...) to build the final result.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The pipeline stages illustrated with a round box are fully programmable.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] The application provides a shader program that describes the exact operations to be completed for that stage.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Many stages are optional and can be disabled altogether.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] In Direct3D 5 to 9, when new versions of the API introduced support for new hardware capabilities, most of them were optional – each graphics vendor maintained their own set of supported features in addition to the basic required functionality.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Support for individual features had to be determined using "capability bits" or "caps", making cross-vendor graphics programming a complex task.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 10 introduced a much simplified set of mandatory hardware requirements based on most popular Direct3D 9 capabilities which all supporting graphics cards had to adhere to, with only a few optional capabilities for supported texture formats and operations.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 10.1 added a few new mandatory hardware requirements, and to remain compatible with 10.0 hardware and drivers, these features were encapsulated in two sets called "feature levels", with 10.1 level forming a superset of 10.0 level.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] As Direct3D 11.0, 11.1 and 12 added support for new hardware, new mandatory capabilities were further grouped in upper feature levels.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 11 also introduced "10level9", a subset of the Direct3D 10 API with three feature levels encapsulating various Direct3D 9 cards with WDDM drivers, and Direct3D 11.1 re-introduced a few optional features for all levels, which were expanded in Direct3D 11.2 and later versions.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] This approach allows developers to unify the rendering pipeline and use a single version of the API on both newer and older hardware, taking advantage of performance and usability improvements in the newer runtime.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Each upper level is a strict superset of a lower level, with only a few new or previously optional features that move to the core functionality on an upper level.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] More advanced features in a major revision of the Direct3D API such as new shader models and rendering stages are only exposed on up-level hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Separate capabilities exist to indicate support for specific texture operations and resource formats; these are specified per each texture format using a combination of capability flags.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Feature levels use underscore as a delimiter (i.e.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] "12_1"), while API/runtime versions use dot (i.e.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 12 for Windows 10 requires graphics hardware conforming to feature levels 11_0 and 11_1 which support virtual memory address translations and requires WDDM 2.0 drivers.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] There are two new feature levels, 12_0 and 12_1, which include some new features exposed by Direct3D 12 that are optional on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Some previously optional features are realigned as baseline on levels 11_0 and 11_1.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Shader Model 6.0 has been released with Windows 10 Creators Update and requires Windows 10 Anniversary Update, WDDM 2.1 drivers.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Direct3D 12 introduces a revamped resource binding model which allows explicit control of memory.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Abstract "resource view" objects are now represented with resource descriptors, which are allocated using memory heaps and tables.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Resource Binding tiers define maximum number of resources that can be addressed using CBV (constant buffer view), SRV (shader resource view) and UAV (unordered access view), as well as texture sampler units.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p01] Tier 3 hardware allows fully bindless resources only restricted by the size of the descriptor heap, while Tier 1 and Tier 2 hardware impose some limits on the number of descriptors ("views") that can be used simultaneously.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] WDDM driver model in Windows Vista and higher supports arbitrarily large number of execution contexts (or threads) in hardware or in software.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Windows XP only supported multitasked access to Direct3D, where separate applications could execute in different windows and be hardware accelerated, and the OS had limited control about what the GPU could do and the driver could switch execution threads arbitrarily.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] The ability to execute the runtime in a multi-threaded mode has been introduced with Direct3D 11 runtime.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Each execution context is presented with a resource view of the GPU.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Execution contexts are protected from each other, however a rogue or badly written app can take control of the execution in the user-mode driver and could potentially access data from another process within GPU memory by sending modified commands.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Though protected from access by another app, a well-written app still needs to protect itself against failures and device loss caused by other applications.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] The OS manages the threads all by itself, allowing the hardware to switch from one thread to the other when appropriate, and also handles memory management and paging (to system memory and to disk) via integrated OS-kernel memory management.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Finer-grained context switching, i.e. being able to switch two execution threads at the shader-instruction level instead of the single-command level or even batch of commands, was introduced in WDDM/DXGI 1.2 which shipped with Windows 8.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] This overcomes a potential scheduling problem when application would have very long execution of a single command/batch of commands and will have to be terminated by the OS watchdog timer.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] WDDM 2.0 and DirectX 12 have been reengineered to allow fully multithreaded draw calls.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] This was achieved by making all resources immutable (i.e. read-only), serializing the rendering states and using draw call bundles.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] This avoids complex resource management in the kernel-mode driver, making possible multiple reentrant calls to the user-mode driver via concurrent executions contexts supplied by separate rendering threads in the same application.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Direct3D Mobile is derived from Direct3D but has a smaller memory footprint.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Windows CE provides Direct3D Mobile support.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] The following alternative implementations of Direct3D API exist.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] There are several functions that provide complex operations over 3D meshes like tangent-space computation, mesh simplification, precomputed radiance transfer, optimizing for vertex cache friendliness and stripification, and generators for 3D text meshes.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] 2D features include classes for drawing screen-space lines, text and sprite based particle systems.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] Spatial functions include various intersection routines, conversion from/to barycentric coordinates and bounding box/sphere generators.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] D3DX is provided as a dynamic link library (DLL).
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] D3DX is deprecated from Windows 8 onward and can't be used in Windows Store apps.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] DXUT (also called the sample framework) is a layer built on top of the Direct3D API.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] The framework is designed to help the programmer spend less time with mundane tasks, such as creating a window, creating a device, processing Windows messages and handling device events.
[src:directx-graphics/direct3d-12-p02] DXUT have been removed with the Windows SDK 8.0 and now distributed as source via CodePlex.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] The DirectCompute API brings enhanced multi-threading capabilities to leverage the emerging advanced compute resources.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] The API is designed for non-graphical applications to access and use GPU resources.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] The Compute pipeline is a type of graphics pipeline used for dispatching and executing compute shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] Compute pipelines are run through compute command lists, which are restricted to recording only copy and compute commands.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] Compute shaders are used for general-purpose algorithms and computations, and are run through parallel processors on the GPU.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] This parallel execution model done by the compute pipeline is organized into a dispatch, thread groups, and threads.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] The dispatch is a 3-dimensional container of thread groups, and a thread group is a 3-dimensional container of threads.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] This pipeline allows for workloads to be easily sent to the GPU without the need for restructuring all of a program's code.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] A typical compute pipeline contains a read-only shader resource view as an input, constant buffer views for additional resource constants, and an unordered access view for an output.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] It is important to set the resource states of these resources in order to improve performance.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] The initialization of the compute pipeline involves creating the root signature, reading the compute shader, and creating the pipeline state object.
[src:directx-graphics/directcompute] After the initialization of the compute pipeline, every frame, the pipeline state must be set, the compute root signature must be set, and the dispatch is run.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] The command list *DispatchRays,* is the start of the rays that are used to generate the reflection graphics.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] These are used by the GPU to begin the raytracing process.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] New HLSL shaders, *ray-generation, closest-hit, any hit,* and *miss*, that are used describe computationally what DXR is doing when rendering raytracing.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] These shaders utilize the *TraceRay* function in HLSL to trace rays in the environment.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] When the ray interacts with the generated plane it can call on one of many selected hit or miss shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] The variation of hit and miss shaders creates different textures.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] *Raytracing pipeline state*, a counterpart to the current Graphics and Compute pipeline state objects.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] Pipeline state objects are hardware settings that determine how the GPU interprets and renders information.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] DXR starts by sending out a ray from each pixel on a given plane and calculates which objects on the plane are hit by the ray first.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] Next, the DXR algorithm estimates the amount of light where the ray intersects the object and attaches that calculation to the object.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] Objects can have different properties that will absorb or reflect light at different rates.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] To stop infinite bounces of a ray from happening, DXR will stop calculations after a certain amount of intersections.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] Rays that never interact with an object are tracked for how far they have gone.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] This is so the algorithm understands when rays have gone too far.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] DXR was released to the public on October 10, 2018 with the Windows 10 October update (version 1809).
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] The first major update was made to DXR on May 27, 2020 with the Windows 10 May update (version 2004).
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] The May update implemented DXR Tier 1.1, which allows game engines to make real time calculations which makes the raytracing graphics faster and more efficient.
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] During GDC 2025, Microsoft announced the next update to DXR (1.2) that will include standardized support for Opacity Micro-maps (OMM) and Shader Execution Reordering (SER).
[src:directx-graphics/directx-raytracing] Major hardware vendors had announced official statements that they will implement the updated API spec into their products.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D (the 3D graphics API within DirectX) is widely used in the development of video games for Microsoft Windows and the Xbox line of consoles.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D is also used by other software applications for visualization and graphics tasks such as CAD/CAM engineering.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] As Direct3D is the most widely publicized component of DirectX, it is common to see the names "DirectX" and "Direct3D" used interchangeably.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The DirectX software development kit (SDK) consists of runtime libraries in redistributable binary form, along with accompanying documentation and headers for use in coding.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Originally, the runtimes were only installed by games or explicitly by the user.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Windows 95 did not launch with DirectX, but DirectX was included with Windows 95 OEM Service Release 2.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Windows 98 and Windows NT 4.0 both shipped with DirectX, as has every version of Windows released since.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The SDK is available as a free download.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] While the runtimes are proprietary, closed-source software, source code is provided for most of the SDK samples.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Starting with the release of Windows 8 Developer Preview, DirectX SDK has been integrated into Windows SDK.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In late 1994, Microsoft was ready to release Windows 95, its next operating system.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] An important factor in its value to consumers was the programs that would be able to run on it.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] There were also strong fears of compatibility; a notable case of this was from *Disney's Animated Storybook: The Lion King* which was based on the WinG programming interface.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Due to numerous incompatible graphics drivers from new Compaq computers that were not tested with the WinG interface which came bundled with the game, it crashed so frequently on many desktop systems that parents had flooded Disney's call-in help lines.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Another Microsoft employee, Craig Eisler, had joined the Windows 95 multimedia team to work on game technology.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Needing program management support, Eisler recruited Eric Engstrom, and together they were granted 11 patents for their DirectX work.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The project was codenamed the Manhattan Project, like the World War II project of the same name, and the idea was to displace the Japanese-developed video game consoles with personal computers running Microsoft's operating system.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It had initially used the radiation symbol as its logo but Microsoft asked the team to change the logo.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Management did not agree to the project as they were already writing off Windows as a gaming platform, but the three committed towards this project's development.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Their rebellious nature led Brad Silverberg, the senior vice president of Microsoft's office products, to name the trio the "Beastie Boys".
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Most of the work by the three was done among other assigned projects starting near the end of 1994.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Within four months and with input from several hardware manufacturers, the team had developed the first set of application programming interfaces (APIs) which they presented at the 1995 Game Developers Conference.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The SDK included libraries implementing DirectDraw for bit-mapped graphics, DirectSound for audio, and DirectPlay for communication between players over a network.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The "Direct" part of the library was so named as these routines bypassed existing core Windows 95 routines and accessed the computer hardware only via a hardware abstraction layer (HAL).
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Though the team had named it the "Game SDK" (software development kit), the name "DirectX" came from one journalist that had mocked the naming scheme of the various libraries.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The team opted to continue to use that naming scheme and call the project DirectX.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The first version of DirectX was released in September 1995 as the Windows Game SDK.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Its DirectDraw component was the Win32 replacement for the DCI and WinG APIs for Windows 3.1.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX allowed all versions of Microsoft Windows, starting with Windows 95, to incorporate high-performance multimedia.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Eisler wrote about the frenzy to build DirectX 1 through 5 in his blog.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] To get more developers on board DirectX, Microsoft approached id Software's John Carmack and offered to port *Doom* and *Doom 2* from MS-DOS to DirectX, free of charge, with id retaining all publishing rights to the game.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Carmack agreed, and Microsoft's Gabe Newell led the porting project.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The first game was released as *Doom 95* in August 1996, the first published DirectX game.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Microsoft promoted the game heavily with Bill Gates appearing in ads for the title.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX 2.0 became a built-in component of Windows with the releases of Windows 95 OSR2 and Windows NT 4.0 in mid-1996.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Since Windows 95 itself was still new and few games had been released for it, Microsoft engaged in heavy promotion of DirectX to developers who were generally distrustful of Microsoft's ability to build a gaming platform in Windows.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] John, the evangelist for DirectX, staged an elaborate event at the 1996 Computer Game Developers Conference which game developer Jay Barnson described as a Roman theme, including real lions, togas, and something resembling an indoor carnival.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It was at this event that Microsoft first introduced Direct3D, and demonstrated multiplayer *MechWarrior 2* being played over the Internet.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The DirectX team faced the challenging task of testing each DirectX release against an array of computer hardware and software.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] A variety of different graphics cards, audio cards, motherboards, CPUs, input devices, games, and other multimedia applications were tested with each beta and final release.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The DirectX team also built and distributed tests that allowed the hardware industry to confirm that new hardware designs and driver releases would be compatible with DirectX.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Prior to the addition of Direct3D to DirectX, Microsoft had added OpenGL to its Windows NT platform.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] OpenGL had been designed as a cross-platform, window system independent software interface to graphics hardware by Silicon Graphics, Inc. to bring 3D graphics programming into the mainstream of application programming.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It could also be used for 2D graphics and imaging, and was controlled by the Architectural Review Board (ARB), which included Microsoft.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D was intended to be a Microsoft controlled alternative to OpenGL, focused initially on game use.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] As 3D gaming grew, game developers discovered that OpenGL could also be used effectively for game development.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] At that point, a "battle" began between supporters of the cross-platform OpenGL and the Windows-only Direct3D.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Incidentally, OpenGL was supported at Microsoft by the DirectX team.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] If a developer chose to use the OpenGL 3D graphics API in computer games, the other APIs of DirectX besides Direct3D were often combined with OpenGL, since OpenGL does not include all of DirectX's functionality, such as sound or joystick support.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In a console-specific variant, Direct3D was used as a basis for Microsoft's Xbox, Xbox 360 and Xbox One console API.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The implementation was developed jointly between Microsoft and Nvidia, which developed the custom graphics hardware used by the original Xbox.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The Xbox API was similar to Direct3D 8.1, but is non-updateable like other console technologies.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The Xbox was code named DirectXbox, but this was shortened to Xbox for its commercial name.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In 2002, with the release of DirectX 9, Direct3D received support for the use of much longer shader programs than before with pixel and vertex shader version 2.0.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Microsoft has continued to update the DirectX suite since then, introducing Shader Model 3.0 in DirectX 9.0c, released in August 2004.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] As of April 2005, DirectShow was removed from DirectX and moved to the Microsoft Platform SDK instead.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX has been confirmed to be present in Microsoft's Windows Phone 8.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Real-time raytracing was announced as DXR in 2018.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Support for compiling HLSL to SPIR-V was also added in the DirectX Shader Compiler the same year.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX functionality is provided in the form of COM-style objects and interfaces.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Additionally, while not DirectX components themselves, managed objects have been built on top of some parts of DirectX, such as Managed Direct3D and the XNA graphics library on top of Direct3D 9.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Microsoft distributes the debugging tool for DirectX called "PIX".
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Introduced by Microsoft in 2002, DirectX 9 was a significant release in the DirectX family.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It brought many important features and enhancements to the graphics capabilities of Windows.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] At the time of its release, it supported Windows 98, Windows Me, Windows 2000, and Windows XP.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] As of August 2024 it remains supported by all subsequent versions of Windows for backward compatibility.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] One of the key features introduced in Direct3D 9 was Shader Model 2.0, which included Pixel Shader 2.0 and Vertex Shader 2.0.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] These allowed for more complex and realistic graphics rendering.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It also brought much needed performance improvements through better hardware acceleration capabilities, and better utilization of GPU resources.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It also introduced HLSL, which provided a more accessible way for developers to produce shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX 9 had a significant impact on game development.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Many games from the mid-2000s to early 2010s were developed using DirectX 9 and it became a standard target for developers.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Even today, some games still use DirectX 9 as an option for older or less powerful hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] A major update to the DirectX API, DirectX 10 shipped with and was only available with Windows Vista (launched in late 2006) and later.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Previous versions of Windows such as Windows XP are not able to run DirectX 10-exclusive applications.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Programs running on Windows XP are limited to DirectX 9.0c, which is the latest major version available.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The DirectPlay DPLAY.DLL was also removed and was replaced with dplayx.dll; games that rely on this DLL must duplicate it and rename it to dplay.dll.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 10.1 is an incremental update of Direct3D 10.0 which shipped with, and required, Windows Vista Service Pack 1, which was released in February 2008.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] This release mainly sets a few more image quality standards for graphics vendors, while giving developers more control over image quality.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It also adds support for cube map arrays, separate blend modes per-MRT, coverage mask export from a pixel shader, ability to run pixel shader per sample, access to multi-sampled depth buffers and requires that the video card supports Shader Model 4.1 or higher and 32-bit floating-point operations.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 10.1 still fully supports Direct3D 10 hardware, but in order to utilize all of the new features, updated hardware is required.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Microsoft unveiled DirectX 11 at the Gamefest 08 event in Seattle.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The Final Platform Update launched for Windows Vista on October 27, 2009, which was a week after the initial release of Windows 7, which launched with Direct3D 11 as a base standard.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Major scheduled features including GPGPU software support (DirectCompute), and Direct3D 11 with tessellation support and improved multi-threading support to assist video game developers in developing games that better utilize multi-core processors.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Parts of the new API such as multi-threaded resource handling can be supported on Direct3D 9/10/10.1-class hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Hardware tessellation and Shader Model 5.0 require Direct3D 11 supporting hardware.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 11 is a strict superset of Direct3D 10.1 — all hardware and API features of version 10.1 are retained, and new features are added only when necessary for exposing new functionality.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] This helps to keep backward compatibility with previous versions of Direct3D.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX 12 was announced by Microsoft at GDC on March 20, 2014, and was officially launched alongside Windows 10 on July 29, 2015.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The primary feature highlight for the new release of DirectX was the introduction of advanced low-level programming with Direct3D 12, which can reduce driver overhead.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Developers are now able to implement their own command lists and buffers to the GPU, allowing for more efficient resource utilization through parallel computation.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Lead developer Max McMullen stated that the main goal of Direct3D 12 is to achieve "console-level efficiency on phone, tablet and PC".
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The release of Direct3D 12 comes alongside other initiatives for low-overhead graphics APIs including AMD's Mantle for AMD graphics cards, Apple's Metal for iOS and macOS and Khronos Group's cross-platform Vulkan.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Multiadapter support will feature in Direct3D 12 allowing developers to utilize multiple GPUs on a system simultaneously; multi-GPU (mGPU) support was previously dependent on vendor implementations such as AMD CrossFireX or NVIDIA SLI.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 12 is supported on all Fermi and later Nvidia GPUs, on AMD's GCN-based chips and on Intel's Haswell and later processors' graphics units.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] At SIGGRAPH 2014, Intel released a demo showing a computer generated asteroid field, in which Direct3D 12 was claimed to be 50–70% more efficient than Direct3D 11 in rendering speed and CPU power consumption.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The performance improvements of Direct3D 12 on the Xbox are not as substantial as on the PC.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In March 2018, DirectX Raytracing (DXR) was announced, capable of real-time ray-tracing on supported hardware, and the DXR API was added in the Windows 10 October 2018 update.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In 2019 Microsoft announced the arrival of DirectX 12 to Windows 7 but only as a plug-in for certain game titles.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Microsoft revealed DirectX 12 Ultimate in March 2020.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] DirectX 12 Ultimate will unify to a common library on both Windows 10 computers and the Xbox Series X and other ninth-generation Xbox consoles.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Among the new features in Ultimate includes DirectX Raytracing 1.1, Variable Rate Shading, which gives programmers control over the level of detail of shading depending on design choices, Mesh Shaders, and Sampler Feedback.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The version number as reported by Microsoft's DxDiag tool (version 4.09.0000.0900 and higher) use the x.xx.xxxx.xxxx format for version numbers.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] However, the DirectX and Windows XP MSDN page claims that the registry always has been in the x.xx.xx.xxxx format.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Therefore, when the above table lists a version as '4.09.00.0904' Microsoft's DxDiag tool may have it as '4.09.0000.0904'.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] APIs such as Direct3D and DirectSound need to interact with hardware, and they do this through a device driver.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Hardware manufacturers have to write these drivers for a particular DirectX version's device driver interface (or DDI), and test each individual piece of hardware to make them DirectX compatible.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Some hardware devices have only DirectX compatible drivers (in other words, one must install DirectX in order to use that hardware).
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Early versions of DirectX included an up-to-date library of all of the DirectX compatible drivers currently available.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] This practice was stopped however, in favor of the web-based Windows Update driver-update system, which allowed users to download only the drivers relevant to their hardware, rather than the entire library.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Prior to DirectX 10, DirectX runtime was designed to be *backward compatible* with older drivers, meaning that newer versions of the APIs were designed to interoperate with older drivers written against a previous version's DDI.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The application programmer had to query the available hardware capabilities using a complex system of "cap bits" each tied to a particular hardware feature.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 7 and earlier would work on any version of the DDI, Direct3D 8 requires a minimum DDI level of 6 and Direct3D 9 requires a minimum DDI level of 7.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] However, the Direct3D 10 runtime in Windows Vista cannot run on older hardware drivers due to the significantly updated DDI, which requires a unified feature set and abandons the use of "cap bits".
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Direct3D 10.1 introduces "feature levels" 10_0 and 10_1, which allow use of only the hardware features defined in the specified version of Direct3D API.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Feature level 11_1 has been introduced with Direct3D 11.1.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In 2002, Microsoft released a version of DirectX compatible with the Microsoft .NET Framework, thus allowing programmers to take advantage of DirectX functionality from within .NET applications using compatible languages such as managed C++ or the use of the C# programming language.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] This API was known as "Managed DirectX" (or MDX for short), and claimed to operate at 98% of performance of the underlying native DirectX APIs.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] In December 2005, February 2006, April 2006, and August 2006, Microsoft released successive updates to this library, culminating in a beta version called Managed DirectX 2.0.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] While Managed DirectX 2.0 consolidated functionality that had previously been scattered over multiple assemblies into a single assembly, thus simplifying dependencies on it for software developers, development on this version has subsequently been discontinued, and it is no longer supported.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The Managed DirectX 2.0 library expired on October 5, 2006.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] During the GDC 2006, Microsoft presented the XNA Framework, a new managed version of DirectX (similar but not identical to Managed DirectX) that is intended to assist development of games by making it easier to integrate DirectX, HLSL and other tools in one package.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] It also supports the execution of managed code on the Xbox 360.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] The XNA Game Studio Express RTM was made available on December 11, 2006, as a free download for Windows XP.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Unlike the DirectX runtime, Managed DirectX, XNA Framework or the Xbox 360 APIs (XInput, XACT etc.) have not shipped as part of Windows.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Developers are expected to redistribute the runtime components along with their games or applications.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] No Microsoft product including the latest XNA releases provides DirectX 10 support for the .NET Framework.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] There are alternatives to the DirectX family of APIs, with OpenGL, its successor Vulkan, Metal and Mantle having the most features comparable to Direct3D.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Examples of other APIs include SDL, Allegro, OpenMAX, OpenML, OpenAL, OpenCL, FMOD, SFML etc.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Many of these libraries are cross-platform or have open codebases.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] There are also alternative implementations that aim to provide the same API, such as the one in Wine.
[src:directx-graphics/directx] Furthermore, the developers of ReactOS are trying to reimplement DirectX under the name "ReactX".
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] It was developed alongside the **Cg** (short for *C for Graphics*) shading language from Nvidia.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Early versions of the two languages were considered identical, only marketed differently.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Although Cg and HLSL share the same core syntax, some features of C were modified and new data types were added to make Cg/HLSL more suitable for programming graphics processing units.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Two main branches of the Cg/HLSL language exist: the Nvidia Cg compiler (cgc) which outputs DirectX or OpenGL and the Microsoft HLSL which outputs DirectX shaders in bytecode format.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Nvidia's cgc was deprecated in 2012, with no additional development or support available.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] HLSL shaders can enable many special effects in both 2D and 3D computer graphics.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] D3D11.3 and D3D12 introduced Shader Model 5.1 and later 6.0.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Due to technical advances in graphics hardware, some areas of 3D graphics programming have become quite complex.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] To simplify the process, new features were added to graphics cards, including the ability to modify their rendering pipelines using vertex and pixel shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] In the beginning, vertex and pixel shaders were programmed at a very low level with only the assembly language of the graphics processing unit.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Although using the assembly language gave the programmer complete control over code and flexibility, it was fairly hard to use.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] A portable, higher level language for programming the GPU was needed, so Cg was created to overcome these problems and make shader development easier.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Some of them are the same as in C, while others are especially added for GPU programming.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg also features vector and matrix data types that are based on the basic data types, such as float3 and float4x4.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Such data types are quite common when dealing with 3D graphics programming.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg also has struct and array data types, which work in a similar way to their C equivalents.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg supports a wide range of operators, including the common arithmetic operators from C, the equivalent arithmetic operators for vector and matrix data types, and the common logical operators.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg shares the basic control structures with C, like if/else, while, and for.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] It also has a similar way of defining functions.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg implements many C preprocessor directives and its macro expansion system.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg programs are built for different *shader profiles* that stand for GPUs with different capabilities.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] These profiles decide, among others, how many instructions can be in each shader, how many registers are available, and what kind of resources a shader can use.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Even if a program is correct, it might be too complex to work on a profile.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] As the number of profile and shader types cropped up, Microsoft has switched to use the term "Shader Model" to group a set of profiles found in a generation of GPUs.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg supports some of the newer profiles up to Shader Model 5.0 as well as translation to glsl or hlsl.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] GPUs listed are the hardware that first supported the given specifications.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Manufacturers generally support all lower shader models through drivers.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] As in C, Cg/HLSL features a set of functions for common tasks in GPU programming.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Some of the functions have equivalents in C, like the mathematical functions abs and sin, while others are specialized in GPU programming tasks, like the texture mapping functions tex1D and tex2D.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg/HLSL programs are merely vertex and pixel shaders, and they need supporting programs that handle the rest of the rendering process.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Cg can be used with two graphics APIs: OpenGL or DirectX.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Each has its own set of Cg functions to communicate with the Cg program, like setting the current Cg shader, passing parameters, and such tasks.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] In addition to being able to compile Cg source to assembly code, the Cg runtime also has the ability to compile shaders during execution of the supporting program.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] This allows the runtime to compile the shader using the latest optimizations available for hardware that the program is currently executing on.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] However, this technique requires that the source code for the shader be available in plain text to the compiler, allowing the user of the program to access the source-code for the shader.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Some developers view this as a major drawback of this technique.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] To avoid exposing the source code of the shader, and still maintain some of the hardware specific optimizations, the concept of profiles was developed.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Shaders can be compiled to suit different graphics hardware platforms (according to profiles).
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] When executing the supporting program, the best/most optimized shader is loaded according to its profile.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] For instance there might be a profile for a graphics card that supports complex pixel shaders, and another profile for one that supports only minimal pixel shaders.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] The Cg dialect has only ever had one compiler, in the form of Nvidia's Cg toolkit.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Microsoft has released two compilers for HLSL.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] The original compiler was the closed-source FXC (Effect Compiler), supported until 2015.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] It was deprecated in favor of the open-source LLVM-based DXC (DirectXShaderCompiler) with support for newer HLSL features.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Both compilers generate bytecode: while the older FXC used DXBC, DXC now uses DXIL.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] The Khronos Group has also written a LLVM-based HLSL compiler, in the form of a frontend for *glslang*, their GLSL-to-SPIR_V compiler.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Support for SPIR-V means that the shaders can be cross-platform, no longer limiting them to a DirectX stack.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] This task was previously performed by source-level converters like HLSL2GLSL, but the resulting code is often bloated.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] The PlayStation Shader Language (PSSL) is based on Cg/HLSL.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] The ReshadeFX shading language is also based on Cg/HLSL.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Shaders written in ReshadeFX are compiled to OpenGL, DX, or Vulkan and injected into games to act as post-processing filters.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Khronos has since evolved *glslang* into *slang*, a shading language and compiler that is mostly source-code-compatible with HLSL.
[src:directx-graphics/high-level-shader-language] Slang can compile to textual shading languages (GLSL, MSL, CUDA, WGSL), bytecodes (D3D11, D3D12, Vulkan SPIR-V) as well as the CPU.
